<paragraph id="217E36CCAC6BFFB655E0F8FDFF6DFEFE" blockId="5.[188,1400,1886,2019]" lastBlockId="6.[189,1398,265,326]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="146" pageId="5" pageNumber="145">
<taxonomicName id="E6C14D4FAC6BFFB555E0F8FDFE2CF8C0" baseAuthorityName="A. E. Verrill" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[189,426,1886,1912]" class="Gastropoda" family="Vanikoridae" genus="Talassia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="5" pageNumber="145" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="sandersoni">
<emphasis id="13B5EADEAC6BFFB555E0F8FDFE2CF8C0" box="[189,426,1886,1912]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="145">Talassia sandersoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from off Cape Hatteras (
<bibRefCitation id="45504B3DAC6BFFB556D9F8FDFB90F8C0" author="Verrill A. E." box="[900,1046,1886,1912]" pageId="5" pageNumber="145" pagination="139 - 294" refId="ref9343" refString="Verrill A. E. 1884. Second catalogue of mollusca recently added to the fauna of the New England Coast and the adjacent parts of the Atlantic, consisting mostly of deep sea species, with notes on others previously recorded. Transactions of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences 6 (1): 139 - 294. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 7412" type="journal article" year="1884">Verrill 1884</bibRefCitation>
) and is found off the Atlantic coast of the 
<collectingCountry id="59D6765CAC6BFFB55417F821FE05F824" box="[330,387,1922,1948]" name="United States of America" pageId="5" pageNumber="145">USA</collectingCountry>
and into the eastern Gulf of Mexico; in NMNH the 
<typeStatus id="FE7A886EAC6BFFB55686F821FBC4F824" box="[987,1090,1922,1948]" pageId="5" pageNumber="145">syntypes</typeStatus>
(USNM 34447) are stored as well as two more lots from off Cape Hatteras and six lots from off 
<collectingRegion id="E305F82EAC6BFFB55152F806FBE2F807" box="[1039,1124,1957,1983]" country="United States of America" name="Florida" pageId="5" pageNumber="145">Florida</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation id="45504B3DAC6BFFB5512BF806FABAF807" author="Rosenberg G." box="[1142,1340,1957,1983]" pageId="5" pageNumber="145" refId="ref9260" refString="Rosenberg G. 2009. Malacolog 4.1.1: A Database of Western Atlantic Marine Mollusca. [WWW database (vers. 4.1.1)]. Available from http: // www. malacolog. org / [accessed 14 Apr. 2022]." type="url" year="2009">Rosenberg 2009</bibRefCitation>
; this study). The 
<typeStatus id="FE7A886EAC6BFFB55415F86BFE25F85A" box="[328,419,1992,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="145">syntype</typeStatus>
(USNM 34447) was depicted by 
<bibRefCitation id="45504B3DAC6BFFB55676F86BFBCAF85A" author="Waren A. &amp; Bouchet Ph." box="[811,1100,1992,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="145" pagination="73 - 100" refId="ref9418" refString="Waren A. &amp; Bouchet Ph. 1988. A new species of Vanikoridae from the western Mediterranean, with remarks on the Northeast Atlantic species of the family. Bollettino Malacologico 24 (5 - 8): 73 - 100." type="journal article" year="1988">Warén &amp; Bouchet (1988</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 48). The teleoconchs are covered by spirally dotted cordlets of irregular strength and weakly flexuous growth lines (
<figureCitation id="B9FA2A49AC68FFB65052FEAAFF58FEFE" captionStart="Figs 12–21" captionStartId="6.[188,241,1822,1848]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,431,1784]" captionTargetId="figure-29@6.[189,1398,431,1784]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 12–21. Talassia sandersoni (A.E. Verril, 1884), USA, off Cape Lookout, TRACOS2010-32. 12– 15. Subadult shell, H = 2.4 mm, W = 1.1 mm, Ha = 0.9 mm, apical angle = 32°. 12. Ventral view. 13. Protoconch, Wp = 0.38 mm. 14. Sculpture first whorl. 15. Sculpture body whorl. 16–18. Adult shell, H = 3.0 mm, W = 1.3 mm, Ha = 1.0 mm, apical angle = 28°. 16. Ventral view. 17. Side view. 18. Protoconch, Wp = 0.38 mm, arrow at lip. 19–22. Subadult shell, H = 2.2 mm, Ha = 0.9 mm. 19. Side view. 20–21. Protoconch, Wp = 0.38 mm. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6564549" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6564549/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="146">Figs 12– 21</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
